    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-12-15T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-12-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="307"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d307">
                <head>307. Telegram From <gloss type="from">the Consulate General in Dacca</gloss>
                    to <gloss type="to">the Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d307fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27–14
                            INDIA–<gloss target="#t_PAK1">PAK</gloss>. Secret; Flash; <gloss
                            target="#t_EXDIS1">Exdis</gloss>. Repeated to Islamabad, New Delhi, and
                            <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Dacca</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-12-15T05:00:00+00:00">December 15, 1971,
                        0500Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5643. 1. Assistant Secretary General <persName corresp="#p_VPA1">Paul</persName>
                    Marc <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry</persName> has asked that I arrange to
                    have following message (not verbatim quote) passed from him to <gloss
                        target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss>.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Begin message:</hi> I have been informed by Governor
                        <persName>Malik</persName> and General Farman Ali that President <persName
                        corresp="#p_YKA1">Yahya Khan</persName> strongly desires to put a end to
                    hostilities in <gloss target="#t_EP1">EP</gloss>. For this purpose he wishes to
                    arrange with the Indian Govt an immediate cease-fire period of at least two
                    hours in which discussions for this purpose can take place between the military
                    commanders concerned. The President desires honorable conditions for Pakistani
                    troops and protection of civilians. I pass this message to you for what it is
                    worth, since I have no independent means of verification. <hi rend="italic">End
                        of message</hi>.<note n="2" xml:id="d307fn2">
                        <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> passed the message to the <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Secretariat at 11:30 a.m. on December 15 and
                        the Secretariat passed it to <persName corresp="#p_BZA1">Bhutto</persName>.
                            <persName corresp="#p_BZA1">Bhutto</persName> refused to credit the
                        message without authentication from Islamabad. (Telegram 5044 from <gloss
                            target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>, December 15; ibid.)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Spivack</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
